.related-card:hover { border-color: #4a8fe7; transform: translateY(-2px); text-decoration: none; }
.rc-title { color: #ffffff; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 8px; }
.rc-desc { color: #94a3b8; font-size: 0.9rem; line-height: 1.4; }

/* Disclaimer */
.disclaimer { background: rgba(239, 68, 68, 0.05); border: 1px solid rgba(239, 68, 68, 0.2); padding: 24px; border-radius: 8px; margin: 48px 0; }
.disclaimer h4 { color: #ef4444; margin-bottom: 12px; display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; }
.disclaimer p { color: #94a3b8; font-size: 0.9rem; margin: 0; }

@media (max-width: 640px) {
  .header { padding: 60px 20px 40px; }
  h1 { font-size: 2rem; }
  .verdict-card { flex-direction: column; text-align: center; padding: 24px; gap: 20px; }
  .vc-right { text-align: center; }
  .vc-value { font-size: 2.8rem; }
  .table-wrap { margin: 24px -24px; border-radius: 0; border-left: none; border-right: none; }
}
</style>

<header class="header">
  <div class="header-content container">
    <div class="tag">Compiled by Gemini 3.1</div>
    <h1>L3Harris (LHX) Intrinsic Value</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">A clear, step-by-step discounted cash flow valuation based on actual FY2025 financials.</p>
  </div>
</header>

<div class="container">
  <!-- ═══ VERDICT CARD ═══ -->
  <div class="verdict-card">
    <div class="vc-left">
      <div class="vc-label">Intrinsic Value Estimate</div>
      <div class="vc-value">${roundedIV !== null ? roundedIV.toFixed(2) : "N/A"}</div>
    </div>
    <div class="vc-right">
      <div class="vc-price">Current Price: ${currentPrice !== null ? currentPrice.toFixed(2) : "N/A"}</div>
      <div class="vc-status" style={`background: ${verdictColor}20; color: ${verdictColor}; border: 1px solid ${verdictColor}50;`}>
        {verdictText} ({Math.abs(Number(marginOfSafety))}% {roundedIV > currentPrice ? 'Discount' : 'Premium'})
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>The Methodology</h2>
  <p>Valuing a defense prime contractor like L3Harris requires looking past quarter-to-quarter earnings volatility and focusing on long-term free cash flow (FCF) generation. Defense contracts are lumpy, and recent acquisitions (like Aerojet Rocketdyne) create temporary noise in GAAP net income. FCF cuts through this noise.</p>
  <p>We use a standard two-stage Discounted Cash Flow (DCF) model. We project out the free cash flows for the next 5 years (Phase 1), calculate a terminal value for all cash flows thereafter (Phase 2), discount everything back to today's dollars, add the company's net cash position, and divide by the number of shares.</p>

  <!-- ═══ ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>The Assumptions</h2>
  <p>A DCF is only as good as its inputs. Here are the exact numbers we are feeding into the model. No hidden adjustments.</p>

  <div class="assumptions-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="ac-title">Starting FCF</div>
      <div class="ac-value">${fcf2025 !== null ? (fcf2025).toLocaleString() : "N/A"}M</div>
      <div class="ac-desc">Reported FY2025 Free Cash Flow. A strong starting base post-Aerojet integration.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="ac-title">Growth Rate (Yrs 1-5)</div>
      <div class="ac-value">{(growthRatePhase1 * 100)}%</div>
      <div class="ac-desc">Projected annual FCF growth. Driven by robust DoD budgets, backlog conversion, and operational efficiencies.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="ac-title">Terminal Growth</div>
      <div class="ac-value">{(growthRateTerminal * 100)}%</div>
      <div class="ac-desc">Perpetual growth rate after year 5. Roughly matches long-term US GDP growth and inflation.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="ac-title">Discount Rate</div>
      <div class="ac-value">{(discountRate * 100)}%</div>
      <div class="ac-desc">Our required rate of return. We use 9% due to the stable nature of defense contracts, counterbalanced by a significant debt load.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE CALCULATION (TABLE) ═══ -->
  <h2>The Calculation</h2>
  <p>Here is the math, year by year. We take the projected FCF and discount it back to present value (PV) using our 9% discount rate.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Year</th>
          <th>Projected FCF ($M)</th>
          <th>PV Factor (9%)</th>
          <th>Present Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {projectedFCF.map(p => (
          <tr>
            <td style="text-align:left">Year {p.year}</td>
            <td>${p.fcf.toLocaleString()}</td>
            <td>{p.pvFactor.toFixed(3)}</td>
            <td>${p.pvFCF.toLocaleString()}</td>
          </tr>
        ))}
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td colspan="3" style="text-align:left">Sum of Phase 1 Present Value</td>
          <td>${pvPhase1 !== null ? pvPhase1.toLocaleString() : "N/A"}</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ TERMINAL VALUE & FINAL MATH ═══ -->
  <h3>Terminal Value & Equity Bridge</h3>
  <p>We assume L3Harris will operate indefinitely. The Terminal Value captures all cash flows from Year 6 onward.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td style="text-align:left">Year 6 FCF Estimate</td>
          <td>${fcfYear6 !== null ? Math.round(fcfYear6).toLocaleString() : "N/A"}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="text-align:left">Terminal Value (Gordon Growth)</td>
          <td>${terminalValue !== null ? terminalValue.toLocaleString() : "N/A"}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="text-align:left">Present Value of Terminal Value</td>
          <td>${pvTerminalValue !== null ? pvTerminalValue.toLocaleString() : "N/A"}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td style="text-align:left">Total Enterprise Value (Phase 1 + TV)</td>
          <td>${enterpriseValue !== null ? enterpriseValue.toLocaleString() : "N/A"}</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <p>To get from Enterprise Value (what the business is worth) to Equity Value (what the shares are worth), we add cash and subtract debt.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td style="text-align:left">Enterprise Value</td>
          <td>${enterpriseValue !== null ? enterpriseValue.toLocaleString() : "N/A"}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="text-align:left">Plus: Cash & Short-Term Investments</td>
          <td>${cashAndInvestments !== null ? cashAndInvestments.toLocaleString() : "N/A"}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="text-align:left">Less: Total Debt</td>
          <td style="color:#ef4444">-${totalDebt !== null ? totalDebt.toLocaleString() : "N/A"}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td style="text-align:left">Total Equity Value</td>
          <td>${equityValue !== null ? equityValue.toLocaleString() : "N/A"}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="text-align:left">Divided by Shares Outstanding (M)</td>
          <td>{sharesOutstanding !== null ? sharesOutstanding.toFixed(2) : "N/A"}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td style="text-align:left">Intrinsic Value Per Share</td>
          <td class="highlight-cell">${roundedIV !== null ? roundedIV.toFixed(2) : "N/A"}</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ HISTORICAL CHARTS ═══ -->
  <h2>Financial Track Record</h2>
  <p>Before trusting a forward projection, look at where the company has been. Here is L3Harris's 5-year performance.</p>

  <h3>Revenue ($M)</h3>
  <div class="bar-chart">
    {revHistoryFinal.map(r => (
      <div class="bar-row">
        <div class="bar-label">{r.year}</div>
        <div class="bar-track">
