  <p><strong>Key observation:</strong> Margins took a hit in 2022/2023 due to supply chain disruptions and fixed-price contract inflation. However, the FY2025 data shows a strong recovery in Operating, Profit, and especially Free Cash Flow margins, indicating successful execution on newer, better-priced contracts.</p>

  <!-- ═══ SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS ═══ -->
  <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
  <p>Our base case uses 6% growth and a 9% discount rate. Here's what the intrinsic value looks like under different assumptions. The highlighted cell is our base case.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table class="sensitivity-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Discount Rate ↓ / Growth →</th>
          {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
            <th class={g === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100).toFixed(0)}%</th>
          ))}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
          <tr>
            <td style="text-align:left">{(row.dr * 100).toFixed(0)}%</td>
            {row.values.map((v, i) => (
              <td class={row.dr === discountRate && sensitivityGrowth[i] === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>
                ${v}
              </td>
            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p>Notice how sensitive the result is to the discount rate. A 1% change swings the value significantly. This is typical for companies with substantial debt loads, as the enterprise value is large relative to the equity value.</p>

  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Geopolitical Escalation:</strong> Increased global instability often leads to higher, sustained defense spending globally, benefiting LHX's communications and space systems.</li>
    <li><strong>Aerojet Synergies:</strong> If the integration of Aerojet Rocketdyne yields higher-than-expected cost savings and cross-selling opportunities, margin expansion could accelerate.</li>
    <li><strong>Debt Paydown:</strong> As LHX uses its strong FCF to aggressively pay down the $11.9B debt load, the equity value will mechanically rise even if enterprise value stays flat.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>DoD Budget Cuts:</strong> Defense spending is highly political. A shift in government priorities leading to flat or declining defense budgets would severely impact growth.</li>
    <li><strong>Fixed-Price Contract Overruns:</strong> While inflation is cooling, unexpected costs on complex, fixed-price development programs can destroy margins.</li>
    <li><strong>Supply Chain Fragility:</strong> Defense contractors rely on specialized, often single-source components (like microelectronics and solid rocket motors). Disruptions here delay revenue and increase costs.</li>
  </ul>

